category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example demonstrates what is involved in finding the nearest integer that's greater than or equal to a given number.</p>
discussion=<p>This custom function is called with a statement such as one of the following:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> ceiling(it) into field &quot;Total Price&quot;</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> ceiling(field &quot;Incident&quot;) &gt; 4 </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">then</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">go</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">next</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> card</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The first thing this custom function does is check the theNumber parameter. As you can see from looking at the handler, it performs mathematical operations that require that the parameter be a number. But what if the function is called by an ill-behaved handler that passes it something that's not a number? In this case, the user will get an execution error when the handler tries to use the trunc function on it.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>To prevent such a possibility, the handler checks whether the parameter is a number. There are a number of ways to handle bad parameters, but the one used in this example is the simplest: the handler returns an error message (instead of true or false):</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> theNumber is not a </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#FF0000">number</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">then</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &quot;Error: not a number&quot;</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The function's purpose is to produce the next higher number, or to &quot;round up&quot;. We can't use the <font face="Courier" size="11">round</font> function for this, because the <font face="Courier" size="11">round</font> function rounds to the nearest integer, not necessarily to the next higher (so, for example, round(2.4) is 2, rather than 3).</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>However, if we use the <font face="Courier" size="11">trunc</font> function and then add 1, we do get the desired result: trunc(2.4) + 1 is equal to 3.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Are we done? Not quite: there are two cases where this formula does not produce the ceiling number. If the number is already an integer, it is its own ceiling, so we don't want to add 1 to it:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> theNumber is an integer </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">then</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> theNumber</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">else</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">trunc</font><font face="Courier" size="11">(theNumber) + 1</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So are we done now? There's one more case: if the number is negative and not an integer, the above doesn't give us the ceiling. For example, the ceiling of -3.6 is -3, but <font face="Courier" size="11">trunc(-3.6)</font> is equal to -3, and adding 1 gives us -2. If the number is negative, the <font face="Courier" size="11">trunc</font> function gives us its ceiling, without having to add 1. This also works for numbers that are already integers--for integers, trunc(number) = number--so we can simplify the code a bit by just having two cases:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> theNumber &lt; zero or theNumber is an integer </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">then</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">trunc</font><font face="Courier" size="11">(theNumber)</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">else</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">trunc</font><font face="Courier" size="11">(theNumber) + 1</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">if</font></p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Rounding a number up to a ceiling
solution=<p><font color="#0000FF">function</font> ceiling theNumber</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> theNumber is not a <font color="#FF0000">number</font> <font color="#980517">then</font> <font color="#0000FF">return</font> &quot;Error: not a number&quot;</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> theNumber &lt; zero or theNumber is an integer <font color="#980517">then</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">return</font> <font color="#F88017">trunc</font>(theNumber)</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">else</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">return</font> <font color="#F88017">trunc</font>(theNumber) + 1</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">end</font> <font color="#980517">if</font></p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> ceiling</p>
title=Rounding a number up to a ceiling